To understand the optical properties of NGO in aqueous solution, UV–Vis absorbance (Fig. 2
                           A), and fluorescence excitation and emission (Fig. 2B) spectra were evaluated. NGO showed a broad absorbance band enclosing the red region of the visible spectrum to the UV region with a maximum at 220 and 300 nm (Fig. 2A–Table 1
                           ) corresponding to a π-π∗ and n-π∗ electron transition ascribed respectively to the sp2 hybridized carbon atoms (CC bonds) and to oxygen moieties or defects present in the aromatic carbon graphene backbone, in line with previous reports [42–44]. The presence of defects and functional groups at the NGO surface and edges, as well as some distortion from planarity associated with their presence, which confers a certain conformational flexibility to the NGO structure, are the main causes of the observed broad absorption [44]. An optical band gap value of 4.41 eV was calculated based on the NGO UV–Vis spectra using Tauc plot (Fig. S1 – supplementary materials) and demonstrates the quantum confinement effect due to the small size of the CC domains within the graphene oxide backbone [45].

MTT and Hoechst assays were performed to verify the cytotoxicity of CQD, NGO and respective conjugates with DOX, in reference cell line L929 (Fig. 7
                           ). Cytotoxicity was further evaluated in human cell lines BJ-5ta, MCF10A and MDA-MB-231, as represented in Table 3
                           .
